<paragraph blockId="16.[92,1047,1118,1397]" pageId="16" pageNumber="141">
This species was placed in group 12 by 
<bibRefCitation author="BEZZI, M." box="[580,725,1118,1142]" pageId="16" pageNumber="141" refId="ref11358" refString="BEZZI, M., 1924, The Bombyliidae of the Ethiopian Region. (London: British Museum, Natural History), 390 pp." type="book" year="1924">Bezzi (1924)</bibRefCitation>
, a group he used for species with totally hyaline wings, although the wings have a distinct but pale infuscation, as noted in his description. The wings of Tanzanian specimens have a darker and more distinct infuscation than the 
<typeStatus box="[493,542,1214,1238]" pageId="16" pageNumber="141">type</typeStatus>
series but are otherwise identical. This and the following two species are relatively small (
<quantity box="[622,738,1245,1269]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" metricValueMax="1.2" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="141" unit="mm" value="11.0" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="10.0">10±12 mm</quantity>
) and have a narrow abdomen. Together with 
<emphasis box="[323,349,1278,1301]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="141">E.</emphasis>
W 
<emphasis box="[371,463,1278,1301]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="141">ssicornis</emphasis>
they have a pale wing infuscation, lacking distinct spots. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bezzi" authorityYear="1924" box="[169,288,1310,1333]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Exoprosopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="141" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erronea">
<emphasis box="[169,288,1310,1333]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="141">E. erronea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has more intensely yellow scales than these other species but is very similar in appearance to the West African species described below as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Greathead" authorityYear="2001" box="[924,1045,1341,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Exoprosopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="141" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="glossops">
<emphasis box="[924,1045,1341,1365]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="141">E. glossops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but, unlike it, has a minute terminal second ¯agellomere.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="142" pageId="16" pageNumber="141" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="16.[92,1047,1440,1686]" box="[92,199,1440,1463]" pageId="16" pageNumber="141">
<emphasis box="[92,199,1440,1463]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="141">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[92,1047,1440,1686]" lastBlockId="17.[92,1046,132,188]" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="142" pageId="16" pageNumber="141">
Body narrow, almost parallel-sided. First ¯agellomere long and robust, with second minute, so that the antenna appears to have only one ¯agellomere. Legs black with black scales. Wing with discal cell narrow. Fore border with a narrow pale brown infuscation, membrane tinged brown and with traces of spots on crossveins. Pale hair on thorax and ®rst abdominal tergum yellow as are the scale bands on the abdomen. These very wide, more than half width of terga. White scales on katepisternum, coxae and abdominal sterna. Male genitalia similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bezzi" authorityYear="1924" box="[92,232,132,156]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Exoprosopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="142" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevinasis">
<emphasis box="[92,232,132,156]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="142">E. brevinasis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Spermatheca very elongate as 
<emphasis box="[590,616,133,156]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="142">E.</emphasis>
W 
<emphasis box="[637,729,133,156]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="142">ssicornis</emphasis>
. Length of body, 
<quantity box="[936,1039,132,156]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" metricValueMax="1.1" metricValueMin="0.9" pageId="17" pageNumber="142" unit="mm" value="10.0" valueMax="11.0" valueMin="9.0">9±11 mm</quantity>
; of wing, 
<quantity box="[195,310,164,188]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" metricValueMax="1.2" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="142" unit="mm" value="11.0" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="10.0">10±12 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
